ing study design and appropriate stats. Ecology doesn’t take place exclusively outdoors, so the book shares invaluable insights on topics such as identifying your goals, developing professional relationships, reading efficiently, and organizing a field season. Because the currency in ecology is publications, it also suggests effective ways to communicate your ideas through journal articles, oral presentations, posters, and grant proposals. This incisive handbook makes explicit many of the unstated rules that ecologists follow and serves as a practical resource for meaningful conversations about ecology.Provides expanded emphasis on collecting and interpreting observational dataIncludes an innovative new workshop for generating and evaluating creative research questionsGives helpful tips on developing the skills most important to students, navigating your career path, writing efficiently, and more  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEcologyxExperimentsvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aEcologyxResearchvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh  aHow to Do Ecology: A Concise Handbook - Third Edition.  aIan S. Pearse.  aMikaela Huntzinger.  aRichard Karban.  aanimal behavior.  aclimate change.  aecological methods.  aecology.  aevolution.  aexperimental design.  afield biology.  afield ecology.  afield experiments.  afield methods.  anatural history.  aobservational studies.  aspecies interactions.  astudy design.  asurveys.1 aHuntzinger, Mikaela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPearse, Ian S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z97